I often find myself checking for the existance of a variable - i.e. that the variable is neither undefined or null. This often means code such as:

``` js
if(!(_.isUndefined(obj) || _.isNull(obj))) {
  // do something
}
```

A nice shorthand for this could be:

``` js
if(_.exists(obj)) {
  // do something
}
```

Kinda like the existential operator from coffeescript, for those of us who don't use coffeescript.

It may be helpful in some circumstances to be able to specify the 'this' argument for  `_.result` calls, whereby the argument would be become the `this` of the function.

It might look like this:

```
function result(object, property, that) {
  var value = object ? object[property] : undefined;
  return isFunction(value)
     ? object[property].call(that ? that : object)
     : value;
}
```

Just food for thought.

