These custom template settings are needed to mimic Handlebars.js, which uses `{{ foo }}` for content that is to be escaped and `{{{ foo }}}` for interpolated content that should not be escaped:

``` js
_.templateSettings.escape = /{{([\s\S]+?)}}/g;
_.templateSettings.interpolate = /{{{([\s\S]+?)}}}/g;
```

However, when executing the following snippet after changing these settings, a `SyntaxError` is thrown:

``` js
_.template('hello {{name}} {{{name}}}!', {
  'name': 'test<br>test'
});
```

Minimal code to reproduce the issue:

``` js
_.templateSettings.escape = /{{([\s\S]+?)}}/g;

_.template('hello {{{name}}}!', {
  'name': '<br>'
});
```

It does work if I rewrite the regular expressions to something like:

``` js
_.templateSettings.escape = /(?!{{{){{([\s\S]+?)(?!}}})}}/g;
_.templateSettings.interpolate = /{{{([\s\S]+?)}}}/g;
```

